# make

Run the recipes in a `Makefile`. `target` builds a named target (or the first
one by default); `parallel` runs independent targets at once; `dryrun` prints
what *would* run without doing it; `vars` overrides a variable on the command
line. make rebuilds a target only when its prerequisites are newer — the
timestamp-based incremental model. For language-native builds see
@build/rosetta; `just` is the modern command-runner cousin.

| Recipe | Flag | Does |
|--------|------|------|
| `target` | — | build a target (default: the first in the file) |
| `parallel` | `-j N` | run up to N independent recipes concurrently |
| `dryrun` | `-n` | print the commands without executing (preview) |
| `vars` | `VAR=value` | override a variable for this run |

`-j` (jobs) is the easy speedup — `make -j$(nproc)` uses every core, since make
parallelizes targets with no dependency between them. `-n` (dry-run) is the safe
way to see what a target will do before committing. Variables passed on the
command line (`make CC=clang`) override those in the file. `make -p` dumps the
database including all targets; some projects add a `help` target that lists
them. A leading tab (not spaces) is required before each recipe line — the
classic Makefile syntax error.

```just
# build a target (default: the first target in the Makefile)
target name="":
  make {{name}}

# run up to N targets in parallel (default: one per core)
parallel n=`nproc` name="":
  make -j {{quote(n)}} {{name}}

# print the commands a target would run, without executing them
dryrun name="":
  make -n {{name}}

# build with variable overrides (e.g. vars="CC=clang DEBUG=1")
vars +overrides:
  make {{overrides}}
```
